00:25:05.300 --> 00:25:07.850
I don't think people expected
that Germany would cut

00:25:07.850 --> 00:25:11.330
the feed-in tariff rate
quite as large as it did

00:25:11.330 --> 00:25:14.530
in '09 and in '10.

00:25:14.530 --> 00:25:17.060
And some people, who haven't
been paying attention

00:25:17.060 --> 00:25:19.940
to the market, might not
have expected as much supply

00:25:19.940 --> 00:25:23.731
to be available from
China as there is today.

00:25:23.731 --> 00:25:25.980
Those people should have
been paying better attention.

00:25:25.980 --> 00:25:30.930
But that combination of factors
resulted in a much faster price

00:25:30.930 --> 00:25:33.380
decline than what
people saw coming.

00:25:33.380 --> 00:25:35.210
And as a result,
companies that were

00:25:35.210 --> 00:25:40.290
formed in, say, 2007, 2008, and
got venture capital-- and saw

00:25:40.290 --> 00:25:42.430
one of these lines right
here and said, oh, we're

00:25:42.430 --> 00:25:44.990
going to be able to
intersect them in 2010--

00:25:44.990 --> 00:25:47.837
are now looking at these
sorts of prices here.

00:25:47.837 --> 00:25:50.295
And saying, oh, gee, we're not
to be able to intersect them

00:25:50.295 --> 00:25:52.920
in 2010, it's going
to be more like 2015

00:25:52.920 --> 00:25:55.390
before we get our
production costs low enough

00:25:55.390 --> 00:25:58.470
to compete at those prices.

00:25:58.470 --> 00:26:01.020
And so the venture catalysts
are now sitting back thinking,

00:26:01.020 --> 00:26:02.490
so let me get this straight.

00:26:02.490 --> 00:26:04.840
You came to us three
years ago and told us

00:26:04.840 --> 00:26:07.776
that you'd be cost
competitive by 2010.

00:26:07.776 --> 00:26:09.150
But now the story
is you're going

00:26:09.150 --> 00:26:11.690
to be cost competitive by 2015.

00:26:11.690 --> 00:26:14.100
This kind of smells fishy.

00:26:14.100 --> 00:26:16.480
I don't know if I want to
lend you an additional round

00:26:16.480 --> 00:26:18.438
here, especially if I
have to wait another five

00:26:18.438 --> 00:26:19.790
years before you're profitable.

00:26:19.790 --> 00:26:23.600
Let me just cut my losses
and pick up shop and leave.

00:26:23.600 --> 00:26:25.110
And your company will go under.

00:26:25.110 --> 00:26:26.710
So that's happened a few times.

00:26:26.710 --> 00:26:30.070
That's happened in a high
profile way, which we all

00:26:30.070 --> 00:26:31.550
know about-- Solyndra.

00:26:31.550 --> 00:26:35.120
It's also happened to a few
other companies-- SpectraWatt.

00:26:37.630 --> 00:26:39.650
Even earlier ones
at the beginning

00:26:39.650 --> 00:26:42.020
of the financial crisis--
OPTI-Solar and others.

00:26:42.020 --> 00:26:44.785
So the companies that are
surviving right now-- there

00:26:44.785 --> 00:26:48.680
are still more than 100 startup
companies in the United States.

00:26:48.680 --> 00:26:50.980
Dozens and dozens of
startup companies in solar.

00:26:50.980 --> 00:26:53.080
Those smart ones
that are surviving

00:26:53.080 --> 00:26:57.840
are usually in
pre-production stage.

00:26:57.840 --> 00:27:01.230
They don't have big
manufacturing lines, hundreds,

00:27:01.230 --> 00:27:05.960
thousands of people to pay,
supply chains to pay for,

00:27:05.960 --> 00:27:08.370
and customers evaporating,
so they're not

00:27:08.370 --> 00:27:09.731
caught in that situation.

00:27:09.731 --> 00:27:10.480
That was Solyndra.

00:27:10.480 --> 00:27:11.950
They had a big production line.

00:27:11.950 --> 00:27:14.520
They had 1,100 people
employed in that line.

00:27:14.520 --> 00:27:16.950
And they had customers lined up.

00:27:16.950 --> 00:27:19.730
They had suppliers shipping
in materials that they

00:27:19.730 --> 00:27:21.580
were converting into product.

00:27:21.580 --> 00:27:23.760
And some of the
customers disappearing

00:27:23.760 --> 00:27:26.310
were not willing to pay
as high prices anymore.

00:27:26.310 --> 00:27:29.040
And that leads to a very
difficult situation.

00:27:29.040 --> 00:27:31.220
You don't have a
cash cushion, you

00:27:31.220 --> 00:27:32.720
don't have any
reserves in the bank,

00:27:32.720 --> 00:27:34.770
you have to sell your product.

00:27:34.770 --> 00:27:37.460
And you're not able to
compete at these prices.

00:27:37.460 --> 00:27:40.930
It's a recipe for disaster
if you're a mid-size company.

00:27:40.930 --> 00:27:44.280
So small companies can survive
in what I call spore mode.

00:27:44.280 --> 00:27:45.240
They're like a spore.

00:27:45.240 --> 00:27:47.646
They don't have that big
manufacturing line to pay for.

00:27:47.646 --> 00:27:49.020
They can survive
off grants, they

00:27:49.020 --> 00:27:50.570
can survive off venture capital.

00:27:50.570 --> 00:27:52.710
And their cash burn
rate is very low,

00:27:52.710 --> 00:27:54.380
they're developing technologies.

00:27:54.380 --> 00:27:56.761
The big companies have
cash cushions already,

00:27:56.761 --> 00:27:57.760
they have cash reserves.

00:27:57.760 --> 00:28:00.220
They might even be able to
access low interest rate

00:28:00.220 --> 00:28:03.440
loans from banks
that borrow money

00:28:03.440 --> 00:28:06.380
at ridiculously low rates
from the treasury right now.

00:28:06.380 --> 00:28:07.960
They may even have
financial branches

00:28:07.960 --> 00:28:10.430
within their own
company, like GE Finance,

00:28:10.430 --> 00:28:13.360
that can do that sort of thing.

00:28:13.360 --> 00:28:15.550
So big companies are,
so far, surviving,

00:28:15.550 --> 00:28:17.640
the really tiny companies
are, so far, surviving,

00:28:17.640 --> 00:28:19.350
but the market dynamic
is really hitting

00:28:19.350 --> 00:28:22.610
those mid-size companies that
already have a manufacturing

00:28:22.610 --> 00:28:23.260
line.

00:28:23.260 --> 00:28:26.370
And so you hear about layoffs,
you hear about job losses.

00:28:26.370 --> 00:28:28.650
These are often the
mid-size companies

00:28:28.650 --> 00:28:31.570
just trying to go
back to spore mode

00:28:31.570 --> 00:28:35.210
so they can survive this
difficult period until prices

00:28:35.210 --> 00:28:36.360
equilibrate.

