And at that point, you'll start
to see the higher priced US

00:36:15.460 --> 00:36:20.300
and European products
begin to soften.

00:36:20.300 --> 00:36:21.259
Yeah.

00:36:21.259 --> 00:36:22.800
AUDIENCE: If the
oversupply condition

00:36:22.800 --> 00:36:24.522
doesn't get resolved
in enough time,

00:36:24.522 --> 00:36:26.230
does it have the
potential to, basically,

00:36:26.230 --> 00:36:28.190
stall the entire industry?

00:36:28.190 --> 00:36:31.150
And if so, how long
would that take?

00:36:31.150 --> 00:36:34.732
PROFESSOR: Well, keep in mind
that this is just the module.

00:36:34.732 --> 00:36:37.190
There's a whole other dynamic
happening on the installation

00:36:37.190 --> 00:36:37.690
side.

00:36:37.690 --> 00:36:40.148
And the reason I'm not getting
into that in too much detail

00:36:40.148 --> 00:36:42.680
is because it varies so much
from country to country.

00:36:42.680 --> 00:36:44.096
Although I will
say a few comments

00:36:44.096 --> 00:36:46.210
before the end of class.

00:36:46.210 --> 00:36:48.770
If the oversupply
condition continues

00:36:48.770 --> 00:36:51.010
and if the feed-in
tariffs continue

00:36:51.010 --> 00:36:55.080
to be low, what you'll see
is a continued softening

00:36:55.080 --> 00:36:58.710
of the module price
into the point

00:36:58.710 --> 00:37:01.220
where almost all
manufacturers are selling

00:37:01.220 --> 00:37:03.579
below manufacturing costs.

00:37:03.579 --> 00:37:06.120
They're all desperately trying
to reduce manufacturing costs,

00:37:06.120 --> 00:37:07.160
reduce overhead.

00:37:07.160 --> 00:37:09.790
It's forcing them to innovate--
at least in manufacturing

00:37:09.790 --> 00:37:10.960
innovation-- faster.

00:37:10.960 --> 00:37:12.630
Not on product
innovation, not on,

00:37:12.630 --> 00:37:14.254
how do we design this
cell differently?

00:37:14.254 --> 00:37:15.900
But more on the
process innovation

00:37:15.900 --> 00:37:19.520
on the line of saying, gee,
how do we mix the silver

00:37:19.520 --> 00:37:21.960
with the cheaper metal
like aluminum in a ratio

00:37:21.960 --> 00:37:25.130
so that we eek out half
a cent per watt peak?

00:37:25.130 --> 00:37:28.310
Because any small fraction
counts at this point.

00:37:28.310 --> 00:37:29.380
We're desperate.

00:37:29.380 --> 00:37:34.500
And you can think of
this oversupply condition

00:37:34.500 --> 00:37:37.570
as a bunch of horses
running nose to nose.

00:37:37.570 --> 00:37:41.220
And which ones will
begin falling out?

00:37:41.220 --> 00:37:43.500
In the beginning, you could
point to easy candidates.

00:37:43.500 --> 00:37:46.620
Those that have already
begun to go by the wayside.

00:37:46.620 --> 00:37:50.390
But now, companies are burning
through the cash cushion,

00:37:50.390 --> 00:37:52.270
reporting negative profits.

00:37:52.270 --> 00:37:55.390
You see right and left, even the
Chinese tier one manufacturers

00:37:55.390 --> 00:37:59.580
are reporting negative
earnings this last quarter.

00:37:59.580 --> 00:38:03.480
So that's a reflection not only
of the oversupply condition,

00:38:03.480 --> 00:38:05.880
but also the fact that
they're continuing to expand,

00:38:05.880 --> 00:38:08.150
despite the
oversupply condition.

00:38:08.150 --> 00:38:12.335
The idea being, well, we can
withstand one, two, three, four

00:38:12.335 --> 00:38:15.910
quarters of losses as long as
we consolidate market share.

00:38:15.910 --> 00:38:18.370
Once we emerge from this
oversupply condition,

00:38:18.370 --> 00:38:20.350
we'll be able to increase
prices a bit more.

00:38:20.350 --> 00:38:23.290
And then return to a
more sustainable market.

00:38:23.290 --> 00:38:26.600
But we'll be the big dogs and
everyone else will be out.

00:38:26.600 --> 00:38:28.910
So I think all companies
right now are trying

00:38:28.910 --> 00:38:31.780
to play that game of survive.

00:38:31.780 --> 00:38:34.740
Survive this oversupply
condition, make it through.

00:38:34.740 --> 00:38:37.050
Some are able to continue
growing and other ones are

00:38:37.050 --> 00:38:38.119
just stagnant.

00:38:38.119 --> 00:38:40.410
So the stagnant ones are
going to become niche players.

00:38:40.410 --> 00:38:42.480
They won't be the major
players in the market.

00:38:42.480 --> 00:38:46.993
The ones who continue growing
will be 80%, 90% of the market.

00:38:46.993 --> 00:38:49.891
AUDIENCE: Has there been talk
of increasing feed-in tariffs

00:38:49.891 --> 00:38:53.760
to try to keep the
American companies alive?

00:38:53.760 --> 00:38:57.222
PROFESSOR: So US doesn't
do many feed-in tariffs.

00:38:57.222 --> 00:38:58.930
This goes back to the
US case right here.

00:38:58.930 --> 00:39:03.310
So due to lack of leadership
at the national level,

00:39:03.310 --> 00:39:07.696
there are a variety of state
level incentives put forth.

00:39:07.696 --> 00:39:09.570
So these are the policies--
we kind of talked

00:39:09.570 --> 00:39:12.070
about this last class, but to
dive into a bit more detail.

00:39:12.070 --> 00:39:14.900
The rebate programs for
the renewables-- these

00:39:14.900 --> 00:39:16.960
are state programs
plus the utility

00:39:16.960 --> 00:39:19.170
and/or nonprofit programs.

00:39:19.170 --> 00:39:21.360
Utility, local, and/or
nonprofit programs only

00:39:21.360 --> 00:39:22.940
and state programs only.

00:39:22.940 --> 00:39:25.450
So you see, for example, in
the state of Massachusetts,

00:39:25.450 --> 00:39:29.370
we have what used to be the
Massachusetts Technology

00:39:29.370 --> 00:39:30.560
Collaborative.

00:39:30.560 --> 00:39:33.790
There was a bit of a power
struggle within Mass State

00:39:33.790 --> 00:39:36.646
and it got incorporated into a
more centralized organization

00:39:36.646 --> 00:39:37.145
downtown.

00:39:40.100 --> 00:39:42.610
So that used to be in a
nonprofit organization, which

00:39:42.610 --> 00:39:45.390
is now more affiliated
with the state.

00:39:45.390 --> 00:39:48.930
The state also has a rebate.

00:39:48.930 --> 00:39:51.760
We have a very different set of
ways of doing things than, say,

00:39:51.760 --> 00:39:56.304
California, which has a
clean energy commission that

00:39:56.304 --> 00:39:57.970
rates each module and
gives you a rebate

00:39:57.970 --> 00:40:00.140
depending on what they rate
the module as performing

00:40:00.140 --> 00:40:01.060
in California.

00:40:01.060 --> 00:40:03.190
So every state has its
own way of doing things

00:40:03.190 --> 00:40:05.870
and it becomes very
complicated very quickly.

00:40:05.870 --> 00:40:11.150
To enact a national incentive,
beyond the tax rebate

00:40:11.150 --> 00:40:15.110
that is already offered
today, is challenging,

00:40:15.110 --> 00:40:16.720
in this political
climate especially.

00:40:16.720 --> 00:40:18.540
Because anything
that you would do

00:40:18.540 --> 00:40:23.780
to raise the cost of something,
which most likely would come

00:40:23.780 --> 00:40:26.410
from some federal
program-- right now,

00:40:26.410 --> 00:40:28.030
the Republican
Party is demanding

00:40:28.030 --> 00:40:30.469
that there be an offset, a
reduction of spending elsewhere

00:40:30.469 --> 00:40:31.385
within the government.

00:40:34.040 --> 00:40:37.672
Many of the places that are easy
to cut have already been cut.

00:40:37.672 --> 00:40:39.130
And so you've gone
through the fat.

00:40:39.130 --> 00:40:41.171
You're now hitting muscle,
and pretty soon you're

00:40:41.171 --> 00:40:42.680
going to be hitting bone.

00:40:42.680 --> 00:40:45.120
So it's difficult
to enact something

00:40:45.120 --> 00:40:47.450
that the government
would pay for.

00:40:47.450 --> 00:40:49.350
It is even more difficult
to enact something

00:40:49.350 --> 00:40:51.016
that the utilities
and rate payers would

00:40:51.016 --> 00:40:53.480
pay for at a national
level because, oftentimes,

00:40:53.480 --> 00:40:55.610
those powers are
delegated to the states.

00:40:55.610 --> 00:40:58.810
And you would enter a
federal versus state

00:40:58.810 --> 00:41:01.630
fight over that, which would
go to the courts, most likely,

00:41:01.630 --> 00:41:03.770
and be held up there
for several years.

00:41:03.770 --> 00:41:08.030
There are about 18,000 different
independent jurisdictions

00:41:08.030 --> 00:41:10.290
within the United
States governing

00:41:10.290 --> 00:41:12.600
how solar is added to the grid.

00:41:12.600 --> 00:41:14.100
And so what the
Department of Energy

00:41:14.100 --> 00:41:16.450
has done, which I think
is the wisest thing

00:41:16.450 --> 00:41:20.220
to do-- given this situation
that we have-- is to say, OK,

00:41:20.220 --> 00:41:22.060
we're not going to
force anybody to change,

00:41:22.060 --> 00:41:24.977
but we're going to give an
incentive for people to change.

00:41:24.977 --> 00:41:27.060
And like they had in the
Department of Education--

00:41:27.060 --> 00:41:29.100
the race to the top,
where states competed

00:41:29.100 --> 00:41:31.770
against each other to implement
best practices in education--

00:41:31.770 --> 00:41:34.230
they're having a similar
program on the installation

00:41:34.230 --> 00:41:38.340
side of solar, trying to get
various states to adopt a best

00:41:38.340 --> 00:41:39.160
practices.

00:41:39.160 --> 00:41:41.360
To streamline the
permitting process

00:41:41.360 --> 00:41:43.580
to get solar onto the grid
in the most efficient way

00:41:43.580 --> 00:41:45.910
possible, and hopefully
reduce the installation costs

00:41:45.910 --> 00:41:48.449
associated with that.

00:41:48.449 --> 00:41:49.990
So let's turn our
attention, quickly,

00:41:49.990 --> 00:41:52.420
to installations, since
I want to give some time

00:41:52.420 --> 00:41:54.980
to have people ask questions
about their class projects.

00:41:54.980 --> 00:41:56.730
Since time is
running very short,

00:41:56.730 --> 00:42:01.190
if you're hitting up
against a roadblock,

00:42:01.190 --> 00:42:03.500
I want to make sure
that we resolve that.

00:42:03.500 --> 00:42:05.860
I'll say a couple of words
about the installation.

00:42:05.860 --> 00:42:07.690
So a funny thing happened
on Tuesday night.

00:42:07.690 --> 00:42:10.080
I met with a colleague
from Wisconsin.

00:42:10.080 --> 00:42:13.635
And he said, well, I
met the editor of-- I

00:42:13.635 --> 00:42:16.540
think it was an editor from
one of the big journals.

00:42:16.540 --> 00:42:18.030
We'll protect the innocent.

00:42:18.030 --> 00:42:21.700
And this was a very
high-impact scientific journal.

00:42:21.700 --> 00:42:25.560
And he said, well, the
majority of the cost right

00:42:25.560 --> 00:42:30.690
now is in the installation side,
not in the module, in solar.

00:42:30.690 --> 00:42:33.990
So I'm not going to be
interested in any papers

00:42:33.990 --> 00:42:37.270
to my journal that describe
new concepts for PV modules.

00:42:37.270 --> 00:42:39.140
I'm interested in
the installation side

00:42:39.140 --> 00:42:41.894
because that's where the
majority of the cost is.

00:42:41.894 --> 00:42:43.310
And I went, oh my
goodness, here's

00:42:43.310 --> 00:42:44.790
another one who
can't distinguish

00:42:44.790 --> 00:42:47.280
between cost and price.

00:42:47.280 --> 00:42:53.420
So the installation cost right
now-- let's focus on cost first

00:42:53.420 --> 00:42:54.610
and then we'll get to price.

00:42:54.610 --> 00:42:56.830
So the installation cost
in the United States

00:42:56.830 --> 00:42:58.520
is partially
reflective of the fact

00:42:58.520 --> 00:43:01.340
that we have those 18,000
different ways of doing it

00:43:01.340 --> 00:43:04.810
here, versus in Germany, there
is one way to do it nationally.

00:43:04.810 --> 00:43:06.660
The federal government
said, we are

00:43:06.660 --> 00:43:11.070
going to demand that
everybody in Germany

00:43:11.070 --> 00:43:13.010
install in this protocol.

00:43:13.010 --> 00:43:14.810
And the paperwork
is very, very brief.

00:43:14.810 --> 00:43:17.420
It's a couple of pages
to get it installed.

00:43:17.420 --> 00:43:18.870
And the inspection is one.

00:43:18.870 --> 00:43:22.020
And so Germany has a much
more efficient system.

00:43:22.020 --> 00:43:25.560
And they've installed roughly
six to seven times more solar

00:43:25.560 --> 00:43:26.514
than we have.

00:43:26.514 --> 00:43:28.430
And if we remember
experience learning curves,

00:43:28.430 --> 00:43:32.920
when you have the reduction
of cost the more you do it,

00:43:32.920 --> 00:43:34.420
that means you have
three doublings.

00:43:34.420 --> 00:43:36.510
Germany has three
doublings over us.

00:43:36.510 --> 00:43:40.730
And even if you assume a
very leisurely 20% reduction

00:43:40.730 --> 00:43:43.290
for each doubling, that means
Germany is about the half

00:43:43.290 --> 00:43:45.660
of the cost as we are,
because they've done more.

00:43:45.660 --> 00:43:48.620
They know how to do it more
efficiently than we do.

00:43:48.620 --> 00:43:49.120
OK.

00:43:49.120 --> 00:43:50.690
So that's on the cost side.

00:43:50.690 --> 00:43:54.620
On the price side, if
you look around the US,

00:43:54.620 --> 00:43:56.950
you have some states
like New Jersey,

00:43:56.950 --> 00:44:00.210
which had an amazing
incentive program for a while.

00:44:00.210 --> 00:44:02.885
And California's as
well, quite generous.

00:44:02.885 --> 00:44:04.260
So there are
certain states where

00:44:04.260 --> 00:44:05.760
it's almost like a gold mine.

00:44:05.760 --> 00:44:08.010
And so there's no
incentive for the installer

00:44:08.010 --> 00:44:09.530
to reduce their price.

00:44:09.530 --> 00:44:12.150
Their costs can be going
down, but their price

00:44:12.150 --> 00:44:13.720
can be maintained high.

00:44:13.720 --> 00:44:16.280
And usually-- this
isn't always the case,

00:44:16.280 --> 00:44:19.870
but in most industries--
when prices are high,

00:44:19.870 --> 00:44:21.620
the industry becomes lazy.

00:44:21.620 --> 00:44:24.605
Now this isn't always the
case, but is often the case.

00:44:24.605 --> 00:44:27.140
It is not atypical that
when the prices are high,

00:44:27.140 --> 00:44:31.090
the industry says, oh, prices
are high, that's pretty good.

00:44:31.090 --> 00:44:32.340
I'm enjoying myself right now.

00:44:32.340 --> 00:44:34.490
I'm not going to be
focused on cost reduction.

00:44:34.490 --> 00:44:38.280
It seems that, at least, the
lower level managers suddenly

00:44:38.280 --> 00:44:42.320
become fixated on cost
reduction when it's too late.

00:44:42.320 --> 00:44:44.380
When margins have
already begun shrinking,

00:44:44.380 --> 00:44:47.300
when prices are collapsing,
and when it's do or die

00:44:47.300 --> 00:44:48.150
for the company.

00:44:48.150 --> 00:44:51.517
Then, all of sudden,
cost becomes imperative.

00:44:51.517 --> 00:44:52.850
So there are very few companies.

00:44:52.850 --> 00:44:54.850
The ones that usually
become leaders

00:44:54.850 --> 00:44:57.580
are the ones who
recognize, gee, prices

00:44:57.580 --> 00:44:58.850
can't remain high forever.

00:44:58.850 --> 00:45:01.270
We have to reduce our costs now.

00:45:01.270 --> 00:45:03.210
And hey, it'll be
even to our benefit,

00:45:03.210 --> 00:45:04.710
because our margins
will be greater.

00:45:04.710 --> 00:45:06.585
We'll be able to take
advantage of this right

00:45:06.585 --> 00:45:09.430
now and build up some cash,
so that when the prices do

00:45:09.430 --> 00:45:11.390
collapse, we have some buffer.

00:45:11.390 --> 00:45:14.100
And we can survive the
oversupply condition.

00:45:14.100 --> 00:45:17.880
So installers, right
now, I have to say

00:45:17.880 --> 00:45:22.210
I'm disappointed in our
installers in the United States

00:45:22.210 --> 00:45:24.550
for not doing more
amongst themselves

00:45:24.550 --> 00:45:26.600
to reduce the
amount of paperwork.

00:45:26.600 --> 00:45:30.510
For not taking a leadership
role in reducing the paperwork

00:45:30.510 --> 00:45:31.260
burden.

00:45:31.260 --> 00:45:34.060
And the true cost of installing
PV on the balances system,

00:45:34.060 --> 00:45:35.500
[INAUDIBLE] installation side.

00:45:35.500 --> 00:45:38.480
I think that's a very
resolvable problem.

00:45:38.480 --> 00:45:41.530
You look to Germany and you have
residential systems going in

00:45:41.530 --> 00:45:45.490
for below three euros
per watt peak price

00:45:45.490 --> 00:45:49.140
taking advantage of the low
module prices right now.

00:45:49.140 --> 00:45:52.080
And the fact that the
installation costs in Germany

00:45:52.080 --> 00:45:53.291
are low, as well.

00:45:53.291 --> 00:45:55.040
Because they've learned
how to do it well,

00:45:55.040 --> 00:45:56.748
they've learned how
to do it efficiently.

00:45:56.748 --> 00:45:58.510
And they've reduced
their cost structure.

00:45:58.510 --> 00:46:01.290
So I personally-- I think
there is innovation to be

00:46:01.290 --> 00:46:03.040
done on the installation side.

00:46:03.040 --> 00:46:05.700
I think there's a lot that can
be done with pre-fabrication.

00:46:05.700 --> 00:46:07.310
Maybe moving a
robot out there that

00:46:07.310 --> 00:46:09.697
can assemble things in a big
rack and then a crane that

00:46:09.697 --> 00:46:10.530
puts it on the roof.

00:46:10.530 --> 00:46:13.020
As opposed to having 10
people going out to a house

00:46:13.020 --> 00:46:15.350
and spending a couple days
putting panels on the roof.

00:46:15.350 --> 00:46:16.190
It's not that bad.

00:46:16.190 --> 00:46:17.990
Maybe it's more like a day.

00:46:17.990 --> 00:46:20.860
But it's still a very
labor-intensive industry

00:46:20.860 --> 00:46:22.380
right now in the US.

00:46:22.380 --> 00:46:24.320
So more innovation can be done.

00:46:24.320 --> 00:46:28.810
But the lion's share of
the installation price

00:46:28.810 --> 00:46:31.760
right now is driven
by what I would

00:46:31.760 --> 00:46:34.769
call inefficiencies in the
way installation is done

00:46:34.769 --> 00:46:37.310
and inefficiencies in the way
the permitting process is done,

00:46:37.310 --> 00:46:39.270
the paperwork is done.

00:46:39.270 --> 00:46:43.855
So that's my soapbox
speech on installation.

00:46:43.855 --> 00:46:45.730
By all means, there is
innovation to be done.

00:46:45.730 --> 00:46:48.040
So don't give up on
that side either.

00:46:48.040 --> 00:46:49.450
It's important.

00:46:49.450 --> 00:46:51.180
It's where the
rubber hits the road.

00:46:51.180 --> 00:46:56.684
But I think you can't just look
at the price of modules today

00:46:56.684 --> 00:46:59.100
and the price of installing
the system today in the United

00:46:59.100 --> 00:47:02.040
States-- and realize that
80% of the price right

00:47:02.040 --> 00:47:04.047
now is wrapped up in
the installation--

00:47:04.047 --> 00:47:06.130
and say, oh, well, there
isn't any more innovation

00:47:06.130 --> 00:47:08.030
to be done on the module side.

00:47:08.030 --> 00:47:09.700
You have to look at cost.

00:47:09.700 --> 00:47:12.780
And you have to recognize
that the module cost is

00:47:12.780 --> 00:47:14.952
driven by the efficiency
of the module.

00:47:14.952 --> 00:47:16.410
And the installation
cost, as well,

00:47:16.410 --> 00:47:18.450
will be driven by the
efficiency the module.

00:47:18.450 --> 00:47:20.840
And so the module being
the engine of the system

00:47:20.840 --> 00:47:23.492
is still very, very,
very important.

00:47:23.492 --> 00:47:25.950
And so the work that folks are
doing-- on new PV materials,

00:47:25.950 --> 00:47:29.630
especially-- is important.

